collect() Method - groupingBy() and partitioningBy()

collect() is a terminal operation that collects the elements of a stream into another data structure such as a List, Set, or Map.

One of its most powerful features is grouping data.

Method Signature
<R, A> R collect(Collector<? super T, A, R> collector)

Don't worry about the generic types.

👉 Just remember:

collect() needs a Collector.

What is a Collector?

A Collector tells Java how to collect stream elements.

Common collectors are:

toList()
toSet()
toMap()
joining()
counting()
groupingBy()
partitioningBy()
groupingBy()

groupingBy() groups elements by a key.

Think of SQL:

GROUP BY department

It does exactly the same thing.

Example
List<String> fruits = List.of(
        "Apple",
        "Banana",
        "Avocado",
        "Orange"
);

Map<Character, List<String>> result =
        fruits.stream()
              .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
                      s -> s.charAt(0)
              ));

Result:

A → [Apple, Avocado]

B → [Banana]

O → [Orange]
Another Example

Group people by age.

class Person {

    private String name;
    private int age;

}
Map<Integer, List<Person>> peopleByAge =
        people.stream()
              .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
                      Person::getAge
              ));

Result:

20 → John, Alice

25 → Bob

30 → Tom
groupingBy() Return Type

Usually:

Map<Key, List<Value>>

Example:

Map<Integer, List<Person>>

or

Map<Character, List<String>>
groupingBy() with counting()

Count how many people belong to each age.

Map<Integer, Long> result =
        people.stream()
              .collect(
                  Collectors.groupingBy(
                      Person::getAge,
                      Collectors.counting()
                  )
              );

Result:

20 → 5

25 → 3

30 → 2
groupingBy() with mapping()

Instead of storing whole objects:

Person

store only names.

Map<Integer, List<String>> result =
        people.stream()
              .collect(
                  Collectors.groupingBy(
                      Person::getAge,
                      Collectors.mapping(
                          Person::getName,
                          Collectors.toList()
                      )
                  )
              );

Result:

20 → [John, Alice]

25 → [Bob]
partitioningBy()

partitioningBy() splits data into exactly two groups.

The key is always:

true

false
Example
Map<Boolean, List<Integer>> result =
        numbers.stream()
               .collect(
                   Collectors.partitioningBy(
                       n -> n % 2 == 0
                   )
               );

Result:

true  → [2,4,6]

false → [1,3,5]
Another Example

Adults vs children.

Map<Boolean, List<Person>> result =
        people.stream()
              .collect(
                  Collectors.partitioningBy(
                      person -> person.getAge() >= 18
                  )
              );

Result:

true

John
Alice

false

Tom
Mike
groupingBy() vs partitioningBy()
groupingBy()	partitioningBy()
many groups	only two groups
key can be any type	key is always Boolean
returns Map<K, List<T>>	returns Map<Boolean, List<T>>
When to Use groupingBy()

Use when you want:

employees by department
students by grade
products by category
books by author

Example:

Department

IT
HR
Sales
Finance
When to Use partitioningBy()

Use when there are only two possible groups.

Examples:

Passed / Failed

Active / Inactive

Adult / Child

Even / Odd
Common Interview Questions
Is collect() terminal?

✅ Yes.

What does groupingBy() return?

Usually:

Map<K, List<T>>
What does partitioningBy() return?
Map<Boolean, List<T>>
What is the difference?

groupingBy()

↓

many groups

partitioningBy()

↓

only true/false groups

Summary
collect() gathers stream elements into a collection or another result.
groupingBy() groups elements by any key.
partitioningBy() splits elements into two groups based on a boolean condition.
Both methods return a Map.
groupingBy() is flexible and can create many groups.
partitioningBy() always creates exactly two groups: true and false.
